#week-title("Two", "Putrefaction & The Formation of the Gur")

=== Core Teaching

Once collected, the undetermined water must be deliberately putrefied. This
allows the hidden life within it to fully emerge through controlled corruption.
In the water work, this stage is often called the *Raven's Head*.

The sign of success in this process is the appearance of the *Gur*. This is the
concentrated seed-matter of the water, the alchemical equivalent of the plant
Salt.

#doctrine[
  _"Minerals are born of fermented, putrefied salt and nitre turned acid. Even
  the most fixed mineral substance traces its origin to a putrefied, fermented
  water."_
  #align(right)[— _Golden Chain of Homer_, Part II]
]

=== Practical Protocol: II. Putrefaction & The Gur

+ *Sealing:* Place water in a large glass globe, filled halfway. Cover with
  cheesecloth or a porous oak stopper — the water must breathe.
+ *Incubation:* Maintain dark, warm conditions (30°C–40°C). Traditionally 150
  days.
+ *Turbidity:* The water will become turbid and emit a foul smell. This is
  correct and indicates active fermentation.
+ *Identification:* The sign of completion is the appearance of white to
  brownish, spongy, cotton-like tufts or a slimy mass that settles to the bottom.
  This is the *Universal Gur*.

=== Topics This Week

- Putrefaction as a generator of life
- The stage of the Raven's Head in water
- Recognizing the Gur: spongy tufts vs. common sediment
- Safety: modern rainwater filtration and biological hazards

#inner-work[
  *Ascent and Descent*

  Begin reading Robert Desoille's *Exploration of Subconscious Affectivity*.
  The guided imagery movements — ascending toward light, descending into depth
  — map directly onto the water work.

  Observe the "descending" of the Gur to the bottom of your vessel. Contemplate
  how things must "die" (putrefy) to release their seed for new generation.
]

